{
  "title": "Key challenges we face",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e577d6b9db528f55",
      "text": "[[Platform Earth]] faces the following problems and issues:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a460c33680ba6071",
      "text": "- [[Multidisciplinary Jargon]]. The project spans a number of disciplines, ranging from social objectives, blockchain, systems design, to  modern technical system administration. Communicating these concepts across disciplinary boundaries is hard.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "460d59321b5528df",
      "text": "- [[Knowledge of Funders]]. Institutions, and funders often lack the understanding of decentralised practice, modern software development, and recent advances in the internet - particularly at the management level. Assessment criteria tend to be based on track record and eminence, while experts in the field tend to remain outliers. Pointing this out, is unlikely to go down well on funding applications. Failure to communicate these issues tends to steer projects in unproductive directions.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d56a18d80f074ded",
      "text": "- [[Abstraction of Purpose]].  Investing in infrastructure, especiallly technical and organisational infrastructure, is unpopular. In social organisations in particular, there is a strong desire (driven by their purpose), to rather support front-line services, and concrete projects that deliver direct on the ground benefits.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5b4ad4075dac5d6b",
      "text": "- [[Emperors New Clothes]]. Fancy technology stacks, blockchain, and management gurus, both hypnotise interest, sucking up energy and resources into ill conceived projects, and repulse people and communities struggling with daily oppression. Holding the middle ground between the two is strategically difficult.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8af6e80ce718ecf4",
      "text": "- [[Historical Failure]]. Decentralisation whether social, or technical has very little historical success. Cybernetics, decentralised file sharing, community currencies, and management restructuring have led many (particularly those in a management position), to believe that only traditional centrally controlled hierarchical structures are viable in a modern society.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "052b8e9b9b051182",
      "text": "- [[Diversity of Stakeholders]]. Practitioners in this area tend to be white, male, and socialise in restricted and unconventional circles. Effective design of working systems requires input from a wide range of stakeholders, which if absent from the core team, is expensive and slow to obtain. Consequently product development usually results in failure to deliver, or the delivery of inappropriate solutions."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b74255b0e32cde88",
      "text": "- [[Mavericks are Difficult People]]. Knowledgable people in the area of decentralised cooperative working, tend to be solipsistic, and opinionated. Teamwork in this area is both vital and unusually difficult. A great designer, a passionate software developer, a systems thinker and anthropologist rarely coalesce into a stable functional team without significant external investment of time and resources."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0fafb290607bd34b",
      "text": "- [[Reciprocal Exchange]]. Systems like mutual credit, and the bootstrapping of decentralised federated governance, require an understanding of, and active participation of reciprocal exchange between distinct horizontally organised entities. There are deep rooted psychological, moral, institutional and pragmatic barriers to the adoption of such working practices in the not-for-profit and social sectors, where \"gift\" and \"being paid\" are seen as the only two sides of the coin."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e56604485c72fa13",
      "text": "- [[Short Term Funding]]. Infrastructure projects involved in organisational and systems change, tend to be funded for short term interventions, while the nature of the problem domain requires steady long term solutions delivering slow persistent change."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4ba37a488c739cd7",
      "text": "- [[Management of Private Keys]]. Public key infrastructure is core to every aspect of decentralised governance, from blockchain, to secure and private communications (often required in product development between geographically separate members), to legal governance and democratic control. We therefore require a pragmatic approach to the management and recovery of these keys, without hindering longer term security issues or compromising our aims of creating decentralised democratic governance of the federation. This is a technical and social challenge."
    }
